                        Wait, the source code is open? Can I just compile it myself?
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                        Yep! Cmdr is <a
                            href="https://github.com/vdavid/cmdr"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-[var(--color-accent)] underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]"
                            >open source (AGPL-3.0)</a
                        >. You can absolutely clone the repo and compile it yourself. You'll need Rust, Node, and Xcode,
                        and your build won't be signed (so macOS will show scary warnings). The $29 is for the
                        convenience of a signed, notarized, auto-updating app.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5">
                    <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">What if I regret the purchase?</h3>
                    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                        We offer a <a
                            href="/refund"
                            class="text-[var(--color-accent)] underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]"
                            >30-day, no-questions-asked refund</a
                        >. Between the 7-day trial and the refund period, you have 37 days to decide. That's more than a
                        month. Take your time.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5">
                    <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">What about Windows and Linux?</h3>
                    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                        macOS only for now. Windows and Linux are on the roadmap. Your license will work on all
                        platforms once they're available.
